<p>Some of the advantages are just as obvious- massive redundancy, portability, analytics, ease of sharing, etcetera- all the standard advantages of computers/the cloud. But some are less tangible- the ideological purity of memories being now completely abstract, and the physical infrastructure that hold them being interchangeable.(The theory(cough:ideology) of the singularity is this taken to it‚Äôs furthest implications- even our bodies are interchangeable, not just the physical triggers and the silicone part of the metacortex)</p>

<p>It should be noted that this isn‚Äôt the first attempt to split memory off from the random triggers- To personally comodify it. Since the 14th century, ‚Äúcommonplace books‚Äù have been, well, commonplace- A book in which you note what you find inspiring and useful, be it shopping lists or sketches. An obvious close relative of this is the diary, through which people seem to speak after they have gone- a very literal example of a persons triggers and memories forming the person.</p>

<p>Bringing the same methods- life logging, up to date, we see that the big war being fought in the social media sphere is over pictures- Instagram made a billion, as the joke goes, on showing everyone what everyone else had for lunch. But a picture is more than that- it‚Äôs the easiest media for a person to parse, save video, because it‚Äôs the closest we come to what we see through our eyes. Instagram was simply a stream of images- Places, people, things frozen in time, often in amber(filters). It was a case of ‚ÄúI‚Äôm here‚Äù ‚ÄúI‚Äôm doing this, with these people‚Äù- triggers in their purest form. Uploaded, made virtual, and still sat there five or fifty years in the future to remind us what an awesome time we had. No wonder it‚Äôs the one that‚Äôs been the catalyst for some of the most successful social networks of their times(flikr, facebook, instagram).</p>

<p>But it‚Äôs still not perfect- It‚Äôs a record of where we are in the physical world**- the interesting things that go on are more than the physical. I want to record what I‚Äôm thinking, not what I‚Äôm doing. This is what I‚Äôm currently trying to do with my tumblr- produce as closer image of my head at a given point as I can- and then I‚Äôve got a near-perfect set of triggers for any day I care to remember, and I‚Äôm in fact a long way to offloading my memory- as if my inbox doesn‚Äôt already do that for me. My metacortex will be a real thing, not a concept to argue about.</p>

<p>So, yeah, That‚Äôs where I am, what I‚Äôm trying to do about our inferior memory systems. It‚Äôs not a solution, it‚Äôs an experiment, an awkward flap in what </p>

<p>I hope will be the right direction.If you think it‚Äôs cool, or disagree, or just want feel like it, talk to me about it.</p>

