<h2 id="the-bot-and-the-cyborg">The bot and the cyborg</h2>

<p>The bot is an amalgamation of human and machine, the a cousin of the cyborg, a machine with human bits grafted to copper and silicone, rather than glass grafted into flesh. People build bots, and when people build things, <a href="/Blog/implicitIdeology/">they always leave something behind</a>. </p>

<p>This is, I think, the important consideration when talking about bots- A bot is a capsule of humanity that speaks, interacts, and learns, not a cold machine that slices and dices text. Consideration of solely the text or product of a bot is absurd, an hangover from the first chatbots and their creators urge to compare them to humans, to have them more closely resemble human speech patterns, be that for spaming or turing test purposes. </p>

<p>The bot consists of more than it‚Äôs product- they are the source material, and their code, down to whether it‚Äôs tabbed or spaced.</p>

<p>Bots, at least the markov chained and similar varieties, build their speech, and their performance from the words of others, shredding them and evaluating them, building them into somthing new. </p>

<p>The lazy could simply point to the source material as the ‚Äúhuman‚Äù part of the bot, and let the code languish as pureley mahinary, a filter for us to engage with the humanity of the substrate. </p>

<p>However, It is my firm belief that the code of a bot makes them as much what they are as their substrate- consider <a href="http://awarpedmirror.tumblr.com/">a warped mirror</a> and <a href="http://repeatafteryou.tumblr.com/">repeat after you</a> then you can see this- They speak the same way, because they share exactly the same code, despite being raised on completely different texts. </p>

<p>The human is inextricable from the machine in the bot, to the same extent as it is in it‚Äôs cousin, the cyborg- What would the cyborg be without the machine? Where would it be without the human? It would be something completely different. </p>

<h2 id="personality-of-bots">Personality of bots</h2>

<p>Bots form the personality by forming them by stealing from human-written texts or other work(has anyone made an instagram-bot yet?), and mixing them around until something new forms. the bot is a composite of its input, and when you make a <a href="https://twitter.com/PG_Bible">bot from the bible</a>, it is a patriarchal jerk. </p>

<p>Humans build their personalites the same way, grabbing bits of experience and internalizing them. Obviously, our creation is a lot more complex than bots- we drag an input from an almost infinite number of sources, and our synthesis is, to say the least, chaotic. Possibly this is why we like bots so much- they have a clear motivation, a simple personality, and are fundamentally stupid. They‚Äôre not chaotic, they‚Äôre simplistic. we can feel superior to them, because we can correct their grammar.</p>
